<Base
  title="Sleep habits: what the evidence for sleep hygiene actually shows | Somnary"
  description="Caffeine, alcohol, screens, schedule, naps, room, exercise — a habit-by-habit look at what the human evidence for 'sleep hygiene' really shows, and the honest catch: standalone sleep hygiene is weaker than people assume, and for chronic insomnia the strongest-evidenced intervention is CBT-I. Context, not a grade, and not advice about what to do."
  canonical="https://somnary.vercel.app/sleep-habits"
>
  <main class="page">
    <header class="head">
      <p class="eyebrow">Context · sleep habits</p>
      <h1 class="title">Sleep habits</h1>
      <p class="dek">
        &ldquo;Sleep hygiene&rdquo; — cut the caffeine, skip the nightcap, dim the screens, keep a
        schedule — is the advice everyone has heard. Some of it is genuinely well-evidenced; some of
        it is weaker than the confident tone suggests; and the package as a whole is weaker than most
        people assume. This page walks through seven common habits one at a time, showing what the
        human evidence actually documents for each and where it runs thin — and it ends with the honest
        catch: for chronic insomnia, the strongest-evidenced approach isn't a hygiene checklist, it's
        <a href="/r/cbt-i">CBT-I</a>. This is context, not a grade, and it does not tell you what to do
        or what is right for you.
      </p>
    </header>

    <ContextBanner
      note="Which habits matter, and how much, depends on your own sleep, health, and medicines. This page describes what the human evidence documents for each habit — habit by habit — and routes persistent sleep problems to a clinician and to CBT-I."
    />

    <p class="who">
      <span class="who-tag">Who this is for</span>
      Anyone weighing the usual sleep-hygiene advice for ordinary, occasional bad nights — and anyone
      who has tried &ldquo;good sleep habits&rdquo; and found they weren't enough, which is itself a
      useful signal about what to do next.
    </p>

    <!-- how to read this page -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">How to read this page</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">Seven habits, honestly labelled</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Each habit below carries a plain <strong>evidence-strength label</strong> in words, not just
          a colour, because the strength varies a lot from one habit to the next. &ldquo;Moderate&rdquo;
          or &ldquo;strong&rdquo; means human trials or large studies back it; &ldquo;weak&rdquo; or
          &ldquo;mixed&rdquo; means the evidence is thin, inconsistent, or mostly about mechanism rather
          than whether the habit changes <em>your</em> sleep. None of these are instructions. They
          describe what has been studied, and what it does and doesn't show.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============ 1. CAFFEINE ============ -->
    <section id="caffeine" class="habit">
      <div class="habit-head">
        <p class="eyebrow">Habit 01 · Caffeine</p>
        <p class="strength str-strong">Evidence: moderate–strong</p>
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-title">Caffeine, and how late is too late</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          <strong>Bottom line.</strong> This is one of the better-evidenced habits. A controlled trial
          found a standard dose of caffeine disrupted sleep even when it was taken <strong>six hours
          before bed</strong> — not just right before it.<Fn n={1} />
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Who this applies to.</strong> Regular caffeine drinkers, and anyone sensitive to it,
          who has an afternoon or evening coffee, tea, energy drink, or caffeinated soda. It matters
          more the closer to bedtime the dose lands, and more for people who metabolise caffeine slowly.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>The claim.</strong> That caffeine keeps you awake is uncontroversial; the sharper
          claim people miss is that an <em>afternoon</em> coffee can still cost you sleep hours later.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What the evidence shows.</strong> In a randomised, double-blind study, a 400 mg dose
          of caffeine (roughly a few cups of coffee) taken at bedtime, three hours before, or
          <em>six</em> hours before bed all produced significant sleep disruption versus placebo — the
          six-hour effect on total sleep time was large enough that the authors supported avoiding
          significant caffeine for at least six hours before bed.<Fn n={1} />
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What it does <em>not</em> show.</strong> That single trial used one fixed dose in a
          modest sample; it doesn't set a personal cut-off time, and it doesn't capture how much
          tolerance, genetics, and your usual intake shift the picture. &ldquo;Six hours&rdquo; is a
          finding about that dose in those participants, not a rule for you.<Fn n={1} />
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What changing this actually looks like.</strong> In practice people who want to test
          this move their last caffeine earlier in the day and notice whether falling asleep gets
          easier. The evidence describes the direction of the effect; whether it matters for you is
          something only your own nights can tell you.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Safety boundary.</strong> Cutting caffeine can bring temporary withdrawal headaches,
          and caffeine interacts with some medicines and conditions — if you rely on it heavily or have
          a heart or anxiety condition, changes are worth raising with a clinician or pharmacist rather
          than guessing.
        </p>
        <p class="ask-inline">
          <span class="ask-tag">Ask a clinician</span>
          Could caffeine be affecting my sleep more than I realise, given my other medicines and
          conditions?
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============ 2. ALCOHOL ============ -->
    <section id="alcohol" class="habit">
      <div class="habit-head">
        <p class="eyebrow">Habit 02 · Alcohol</p>
        <p class="strength str-mod">Evidence: moderate</p>
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-title">Alcohol — the nightcap that backfires</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          <strong>Bottom line.</strong> A drink can help you fall asleep and then quietly wreck the
          back half of the night: alcohol delays REM sleep and fragments sleep in the
          <strong>second half</strong> as it wears off.<Fn n={2} />
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Who this applies to.</strong> Anyone using a nightcap to wind down, and anyone
          drinking in the few hours before bed.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>The claim.</strong> The folk belief is that alcohol is a sleep aid because it makes
          you drowsy. The evidence complicates that: the sedation is front-loaded and the cost comes
          later.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What the evidence shows.</strong> A review of the research on alcohol and normal sleep
          found that alcohol shortens the time to fall asleep and can consolidate sleep early on, but
          the onset of the first REM period is significantly delayed at all doses, REM is reduced at
          higher doses, and the second half of the night becomes more disrupted.<Fn n={2} /> The
          familiar &ldquo;knocked out then wide awake at 3am&rdquo; pattern is exactly this.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What it does <em>not</em> show.</strong> This is a qualitative review rather than a
          formal systematic review, and it describes averages across studies, not a threshold dose that
          is safe for sleep or a prediction for one person's night.<Fn n={2} /> It is about sleep
          architecture, not about alcohol's many other health effects.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What changing this actually looks like.</strong> People testing this usually move
          drinks earlier and further from bedtime, or reduce them, and watch whether the middle of the
          night steadies. The evidence points to why the nightcap can betray you; the rest is your own
          experience.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Safety boundary.</strong> Using alcohol to get to sleep can build into dependence, and
          alcohol is dangerous combined with sedating sleep medicines and some other drugs. If a drink
          has become how you fall asleep, that is a conversation for a clinician, not a habit to
          fine-tune alone.
        </p>
        <p class="ask-inline">
          <span class="ask-tag">Ask a clinician</span>
          Is my drinking affecting my sleep or interacting with anything I take to sleep?
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============ 3. SCREENS & LIGHT ============ -->
    <section id="light" class="habit">
      <div class="habit-head">
        <p class="eyebrow">Habit 03 · Screens &amp; light</p>
        <p class="strength str-mixed">Evidence: mixed — light timing moderate, blue-light gadgets weak</p>
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-title">Screens &amp; light — the timing part is real, the gadget part isn't</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          <strong>Bottom line.</strong> Bright, blue-rich light in the evening genuinely delays sleep by
          suppressing melatonin — that part is moderately well-evidenced. But the popular fix, that
          blue-light glasses or a phone's night mode will rescue your sleep, is
          <strong>weak and inconsistent</strong>, and worth separating from the timing point.<Fn n={3} /><Fn n={5} />
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Who this applies to.</strong> Anyone using bright screens or bright room lighting in
          the hour or two before bed — and anyone who has bought blue-light glasses expecting a sleep
          cure.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>The claim(s).</strong> Two very different claims usually get bundled together: (a)
          evening light can push your body clock later and delay sleep, and (b) a blue-light filter
          undoes that. The evidence treats them very differently.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What the evidence shows.</strong> For the light itself, the evidence is solid: room
          light before bed (under 200 lux) suppressed and shortened melatonin release compared with dim
          light in nearly all participants,<Fn n={4} /> and in a crossover study reading on a
          light-emitting e-reader before bed, versus a printed book, reduced melatonin, delayed sleep
          onset, phase-delayed the circadian clock, and cut next-morning alertness.<Fn n={3} /> For the
          <em>gadget</em> claim, a Cochrane review of blue-light-<em>filtering</em> spectacle lenses
          found the effect on sleep quality was very-low-certainty and mixed — three of six trials
          reported improvement, three found no difference — and little or no effect on visual
          outcomes.<Fn n={5} />
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What it does <em>not</em> show.</strong> The melatonin studies are about light exposure
          and clock timing under lab conditions; they don't prove a given screen habit ruins <em>your</em>
          sleep, or that any specific number of minutes offline fixes it.<Fn n={3} /><Fn n={4} /> And the
          lens evidence does not support blue-light glasses as a reliable sleep treatment — the honest
          read is &ldquo;we don't know, and probably little.&rdquo;<Fn n={5} />
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What changing this actually looks like.</strong> The lever the evidence actually points
          at is <em>less bright light</em> in the evening — dimmer rooms and dimmer, further-away screens
          — rather than a filter bolted onto the same bright exposure. People test it by dimming things
          down before bed and seeing whether sleep comes easier.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Safety boundary.</strong> This one is low-risk. The main caution is spending money on
          blue-light glasses expecting a fix the evidence doesn't support, and letting a screen habit
          stand in for evaluating a sleep problem that has run on for months.
        </p>
        <p class="ask-inline">
          <span class="ask-tag">Ask a clinician</span>
          If evening screens seem tied to my sleep trouble, is this a habit issue or a sign of something
          worth assessing?
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============ 4. SCHEDULE ============ -->
    <section id="schedule" class="habit">
      <div class="habit-head">
        <p class="eyebrow">Habit 04 · Regular schedule</p>
        <p class="strength str-mod">Evidence: moderate, largely observational</p>
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-title">A regular schedule — consistent timing, mostly from cohort data</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          <strong>Bottom line.</strong> Keeping a regular sleep–wake schedule is one of the more
          defensible habits, but much of the strongest evidence is <em>observational</em>: large studies
          link regular timing to better outcomes, which is not the same as proving that fixing your
          schedule fixes your sleep.<Fn n={6} />
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Who this applies to.</strong> Anyone with erratic bed and wake times — big weekday /
          weekend swings, shifting bedtimes — who is otherwise reasonably healthy.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>The claim.</strong> That going to bed and waking at consistent times steadies your body
          clock and improves sleep.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What the evidence shows.</strong> In a UK Biobank cohort of roughly 60,000 people
          wearing accelerometers, a Sleep Regularity Index — how consistent the sleep–wake pattern was
          day to day — was a <em>stronger</em> predictor of all-cause, cardiometabolic, and cancer
          mortality than sleep duration.<Fn n={6} /> Regularity, in other words, tracks with health at
          large scale.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What it does <em>not</em> show.</strong> This is a cohort study: it shows association,
          not causation. It cannot prove that making your schedule more regular <em>causes</em> better
          sleep or a longer life, and people who keep regular hours may differ in many other ways.<Fn n={6} />
          It is a strong reason to take regularity seriously, not proof it is a lever for you.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What changing this actually looks like.</strong> In practice this means anchoring wake
          time in particular — including on weekends — and letting bedtime follow. Regular timing also
          overlaps heavily with <a href="/r/cbt-i">CBT-I</a>, where a fixed rise time is a core piece of
          the method rather than a standalone tip.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Safety boundary.</strong> Forcing a rigid schedule while chronically short on sleep can
          backfire; and if your schedule is dictated by shift work, that is a distinct
          <a href="/jet-lag-shift-work">circadian problem</a> that belongs with a clinician rather than a
          hygiene tip.
        </p>
        <p class="ask-inline">
          <span class="ask-tag">Ask a clinician</span>
          Is an irregular schedule the driver of my sleep problem, or a symptom of something else?
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============ 5. NAPS ============ -->
    <section id="naps" class="habit">
      <div class="habit-head">
        <p class="eyebrow">Habit 05 · Naps</p>
        <p class="strength str-mixed">Evidence: mixed — depends on your sleep</p>
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-title">Naps — helpful for some, counter-productive for insomnia</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          <strong>Bottom line.</strong> Napping isn't good or bad in the abstract. For a good sleeper a
          short nap is generally fine or even useful; for someone with insomnia, daytime sleep can work
          <em>against</em> them by spending the sleep pressure that would otherwise help them sleep at
          night — which is why CBT-I's sleep-restriction logic tends to limit it.<Fn n={7} />
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Who this applies to.</strong> The advice splits by who you are: occasional nappers who
          sleep well at night are in a different situation from people struggling with chronic insomnia.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>The claim.</strong> &ldquo;Never nap&rdquo; is common blanket advice — but it is only
          well-founded for a specific group.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What the evidence shows.</strong> The rationale comes from how sleep restriction (a
          core, effective part of CBT-I) is thought to work: consolidating sleep by building up
          homeostatic sleep pressure. A systematic review of sleep-restriction-therapy mechanisms found
          reduced time in bed and shorter time to fall asleep consistent with increased sleep pressure —
          the same pressure a daytime nap discharges.<Fn n={7} /> That is why, for insomnia, cutting naps
          is often part of the plan.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What it does <em>not</em> show.</strong> That same review is explicit that these
          changes are largely observed as <em>outcomes</em>, and that rigorous mechanistic proof is still
          limited — so the sleep-drive story is a well-motivated rationale, not a settled law.<Fn n={7} />
          And none of it means naps are harmful for people who sleep well; for good sleepers the evidence
          doesn't support a blanket ban.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What changing this actually looks like.</strong> For a good sleeper, this may mean
          nothing changes. For someone with insomnia, the CBT-I approach is usually to protect nighttime
          sleep drive rather than spend it during the day — but that is done as part of a structured
          programme, tailored, not as a rule improvised alone.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Safety boundary.</strong> A sudden new need to nap, or overwhelming daytime sleepiness,
          can signal an underlying disorder (such as sleep apnea) and is a reason to seek
          <a href="/when-to-see-a-doctor">evaluation</a>, not to just cut naps.
        </p>
        <p class="ask-inline">
          <span class="ask-tag">Ask a clinician</span>
          Is my daytime sleepiness something to manage with my schedule, or a sign of a disorder to
          assess?
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============ 6. ENVIRONMENT ============ -->
    <section id="environment" class="habit">
      <div class="habit-head">
        <p class="eyebrow">Habit 06 · Bedroom environment</p>
        <p class="strength str-weak">Evidence: weak–moderate</p>
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-title">Cool, dark, quiet — reasonable, but thinner than it sounds</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          <strong>Bottom line.</strong> &ldquo;Keep the room cool, dark, and quiet&rdquo; is sensible and
          low-risk, but the direct human evidence that a cooler or darker room <em>causes</em> better
          sleep is thinner than the confident advice implies. Night <em>noise</em> is the part that is
          actually well-quantified.<Fn n={8} /><Fn n={9} />
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Who this applies to.</strong> Anyone whose bedroom is hot, bright, or noisy — which is
          worth acting on regardless — while keeping expectations proportionate to the evidence.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>The claim.</strong> That a cool, dark, quiet room measurably improves sleep.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What the evidence shows.</strong> For noise, the evidence is real and numeric: an update
          to the WHO noise meta-analysis (36 studies) found that for every 10-decibel rise in night-time
          road-traffic noise, the odds of being highly sleep-disturbed rose about 2.5-fold, at moderate
          quality of evidence.<Fn n={8} /> For temperature, the case is mechanistic: a review of sleep
          thermoregulation notes that falling asleep coincides with the steepest drop in core body
          temperature, and that skin warming can shorten the time to fall asleep — which is <em>why</em> a
          too-warm room plausibly hurts.<Fn n={9} />
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What it does <em>not</em> show.</strong> The temperature evidence is largely mechanism
          and physiology, not a body of trials showing that turning the thermostat down a couple of
          degrees reliably improves real-world sleep — so &ldquo;cool room&rdquo; earns a
          <em>weak-to-moderate</em> label, not a strong one.<Fn n={9} /> The noise finding is an
          association from population studies, not a personal dose-response.<Fn n={8} />
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What changing this actually looks like.</strong> The highest-value move the evidence
          supports is reducing intrusive night noise; a cool, dark room is a reasonable, cheap default to
          try, held with appropriately modest expectations.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Safety boundary.</strong> Low-risk overall. The main caution is chasing an ever more
          &ldquo;optimised&rdquo; bedroom as a substitute for addressing a persistent sleep problem that
          needs a different approach.
        </p>
        <p class="ask-inline">
          <span class="ask-tag">Ask a clinician</span>
          If my room already seems fine and I still sleep badly, what should I be looking at instead?
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============ 7. EXERCISE ============ -->
    <section id="exercise" class="habit">
      <div class="habit-head">
        <p class="eyebrow">Habit 07 · Exercise &amp; timing</p>
        <p class="strength str-mod">Evidence: moderate, myth-correcting</p>
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-title">Exercise — helps sleep, and the &ldquo;not at night&rdquo; rule is mostly a myth</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          <strong>Bottom line.</strong> Regular exercise is associated with better sleep, and the common
          rule that you must never exercise in the evening is <strong>largely overturned</strong> for
          most people — with one narrow exception, vigorous exercise finishing right before bed.<Fn n={10} /><Fn n={11} />
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Who this applies to.</strong> Generally healthy adults deciding whether to exercise,
          and specifically whether an evening workout will cost them sleep.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>The claim(s).</strong> Two claims: that regular exercise improves sleep, and that
          evening exercise ruins it. The evidence supports the first and mostly refutes the second.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What the evidence shows.</strong> A meta-analytic review of 66 studies found regular
          exercise had small benefits on total sleep time and sleep efficiency and a <em>moderate</em>
          benefit on sleep quality.<Fn n={10} /> And a systematic review and meta-analysis of 23 studies
          on <em>evening</em> exercise in healthy adults found it did not harm sleep onset, duration, or
          quality — if anything it slightly increased deep (slow-wave) sleep — with the single exception
          that vigorous exercise ending less than an hour before bed could delay falling asleep.<Fn n={11} />
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What it does <em>not</em> show.</strong> The benefits are averages across mostly healthy
          participants, not a guarantee for everyone, and the exercise-and-sleep link is not proof that
          starting to exercise will fix a given person's insomnia.<Fn n={10} /> The evening-exercise
          reassurance is for healthy adults and doesn't erase the vigorous-right-before-bed
          caveat.<Fn n={11} />
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What changing this actually looks like.</strong> For most people the practical upshot is
          that there is no need to avoid evening workouts on sleep grounds; the only clear caution the
          evidence flags is intense exercise in the last hour before bed.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Safety boundary.</strong> Starting or intensifying exercise carries its own health
          considerations unrelated to sleep — if you have a heart condition or other medical issues, that
          belongs with a clinician first.
        </p>
        <p class="ask-inline">
          <span class="ask-tag">Ask a clinician</span>
          Given my health, is there any reason evening exercise specifically would be a problem for me?
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============ HYGIENE vs CBT-I — the honest catch ============ -->
    <section id="hygiene-vs-cbti" class="habit candor">
      <div class="habit-head">
        <p class="eyebrow">The honest catch</p>
        <p class="strength str-candor">Hygiene is weak as a package · CBT-I is the strong intervention</p>
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-title">Sleep hygiene vs CBT-I — what the habits can and can't do</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Here is the part most &ldquo;sleep hygiene&rdquo; advice leaves out. Taken together as a
          <em>package</em>, sleep hygiene is <strong>weaker than people assume</strong>. In the insomnia
          research it is repeatedly used as the <em>control condition</em> — the basic-advice comparison
          that the real treatment is measured against. And that real treatment is
          <a href="/r/cbt-i">CBT-I</a> (cognitive behavioural therapy for insomnia), the
          strongest-evidenced sleep intervention on Somnary. A meta-analysis of 20 randomised trials found
          CBT-I shortened the time to fall asleep by about 19 minutes, cut time awake at night by about 26
          minutes, and raised sleep efficiency by nearly 10 percent.<Fn n={14} /> Two professional bodies
          name it first-line: the American College of Physicians recommends that <em>all</em> adults
          receive CBT-I as the initial treatment for chronic insomnia, before medication,<Fn n={12} /> and
          the American Academy of Sleep Medicine gives multicomponent CBT-I a strong recommendation.<Fn n={13} />
        </p>
        <p>
          The same AASM guideline goes further and specifically <strong>suggests clinicians not use sleep
          hygiene as a single-component therapy</strong> for chronic insomnia.<Fn n={13} /> Standalone
          hygiene, in other words, is not enough on its own for a chronic problem — a striking thing to
          learn about the advice given out most freely.
        </p>
        <p>
          None of that discredits the habits above for the many people whose sleep problems are minor.
          If you sleep badly <em>occasionally</em> and mildly, these low-risk habits are a sensible place
          to start, and several of them are moderately well-evidenced in their own right. The honest
          framing is about matching effort to severity — not abandoning good habits.
        </p>

        <!-- severity-proportionate routing (evidence-descriptive, never a diagnosis or a directive) -->
        <div class="route">
          <p class="route-head">Matching the approach to the problem</p>
          <p class="route-line">
            <span class="route-tag">Occasional / mild</span>
            For the odd bad night or mild, short-lived trouble, the habits on this page are a sensible,
            low-risk starting point, and the best-evidenced of them (caffeine timing, alcohol, evening
            light) are the ones to weigh first.
          </p>
          <p class="route-line">
            <span class="route-tag">Most nights, 3+ months</span>
            When poor sleep runs most nights for three months or more, habit tweaks are unlikely to be
            enough on their own — the strongest evidence points to <a href="/r/cbt-i">CBT-I</a>, and that
            is a conversation to have with a clinician. Persistent sleep problems, or daytime sleepiness
            and other warning signs, are a reason to seek
            <a href="/when-to-see-a-doctor">evaluation</a> rather than keep adjusting habits alone. How
            Somnary handles interactions and safety boundaries lives on the
            <a href="/safety">safety page</a>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p class="candor-note">
          This describes what the evidence documents and where different approaches fit. It does not
          diagnose your sleep, tell you which category you are in, or tell you what to do — that is a
          judgement for you and a clinician.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Disclaimer placed adjacent to this decision-bearing section, not only in the footer. -->
      <div class="disclaimer-slot">
        <Disclaimer variant="standard" />
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- related -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">Related</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">Read next</h2>
      <ul class="related">
        <li><a href="/r/cbt-i">CBT-I</a> — the strongest-evidenced approach to chronic insomnia, and why the habits above are a starting point rather than the treatment.</li>
        <li><a href="/when-to-see-a-doctor">When to see a doctor</a> — the signs that a sleep problem needs evaluation, not another habit.</li>
        <li><a href="/safety">Safety &amp; interactions</a> — the primary boundary: how Somnary handles interactions and when to route to a clinician.</li>
        <li><a href="/jet-lag-shift-work">Jet lag + shift work</a> — why a schedule dictated by travel or shifts is a circadian problem, not a hygiene tip.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

